ranch in June of 2004. He practiced minimally invasive spine surgery and general neurosurgery for six years in Davenport, Iowa. However, he wanted to be able to offer comprehensive cerebrovascular services and had the forethought to predict the paradigm shift in the field from open to endovascular surgery. In 2010, Dr. Maioriello closed his solo private practice and moved to Houston for his two-year endovascular neurosurgery fellowship at the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston. In 2012, he completed the fellowship and started Minimally Invasive Brain and Spine; a new comprehensive neurosurgery practice covering Houston and the surrounding suburbs.\r\n\r\nHis comprehensive clinical interests include: endovascular surgery for cerebrovascular disease, intra-arterial management of acute stroke, minimally invasive spine surgery, brain and spine tumor surgery, brain and spine trauma surgery, peripheral nerve surgery, general neurosurgery, neurosurgical intensive care, stereotactic neurosurgery, and the surgical management of neck and low back pain.\r\n\r\n<a class=\"linkedin\" href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/pub/anthony-maioriello/25/a33/436\" target=\"_blank\">View my LinkedIn profile</a>','Anthony V. Maioriello M.D., M.S., FAANS, FACS','','publish','closed','open','','dr-maioriello','','','2015-04-17 19:47:10','2015-04-17 19:47:10','',0,'/?page_id=20',0,'page','',0),(21,1,'2015-01-20 17:07:56','2015-01-20 17:07:56','Dr. Maioriello Completed his undergraduate studies in 1993 and earned a bachelors degree in biochemistry from Illinois Benedictine College. After college, he completed a two-year graduate program in less than a year at Northwestern University; receiving his masters in neurobiology and physiology. Dr. Maioriello graduated from Rush Medical College in 1998, and completed his  neurosurgical residency at The University of Texas Medical Branch in June of 2004. He practiced minimally invasive spine surgery and general neurosurgery for six years in