1!4m2!3m1!1s0x8640cadd6b32fd83:0x5655e3f1a711a52\" target=\"_blank\">Bayshore Medical Center</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n                <li><a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/place/Memorial+Hermann+Hospital/@29.7061606,-95.4000822,15z/data=!4m5!1m2!2m1!1sMemorial+Hermann+Texas+Medical+Center!3m1!1s0x0000000000000000:0x66e1040ca602bb3d\" target=\"_blank\">Memorial Hermann Texas Medical Center</a></li>\r\n                <li><a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/place/Kingwood+Medical+Center/@30.050036,-95.254536,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m2!3m1!1s0x8640b2cc466ce099:0x97b0ea783fa397af\" target=\"_blank\">Kingwood Medical Center</a></li>\r\n                <!--<li><a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pearland+Medical+Center/@29.579335,-95.391433,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m2!3m1!1s0x8640935309b6e3cd:0x57d2ca6fa7719736\" target=\"_blank\">Pearland Medical Center</a></li>-->\r\n            </ul>','Hospital Affiliations','','inherit','closed','open','','24-revision-v1','','','2015-04-17 18:48:13','2015-04-17 18:48:13','',24,'/24-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(115,1,'2015-04-17 19:14:00','2015-04-17 19:14:00','Dr. Maioriello was born and raised in the suburbs of Chicago. He completed his undergraduate studies in 1993 and earned a bachelors degree in biochemistry from Illinois Benedictine College. After college, he completed a two-year graduate program in less than a year and received his masters degree in neurobiology and physiology from Northwestern University. Dr. Maioriello graduated from Rush Medical College in 1998, and his six year neurosurgical residency was completed at The University of Texas Medical Branch in June of 2004. He practiced minimally invasive spine surgery and general neurosurgery for six years in Davenport, Iowa. However, he wanted to be able to offer comprehensive cerebrovascular services and had the forethought to predict the paradigm shift in the field from open to endovascular surgery. In 2010, Dr. Maioriello closed his solo private practice and moved to Houston for his two-year endovascular neurosurgery fellowship at the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston. In 2012, he completed the fellowship and started Minimally Invasive Brain and Spine; a new comprehensive neurosurgery practice covering Houston and the surrounding suburbs.\r\n\r\nHis comprehensive clinical interests include: endovascular surgery for cerebrovascular disease, intra-arterial management of acute stroke, minimally invasive spine surgery, brain and spine tumor surgery, brain and spine trauma surgery, peripheral nerve surgery, general neurosurgery, neurosurgical intensive care, stereotactic neurosurgery, and the surgical management of neck and low back pain.\r\n\r\n<a class=\"linkedin\" href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/pub/anthony-maioriello/25/a33/436\" target=\"_blank\">View my LinkedIn profile</a>','Dr. Anthony Maioriello','','inherit','closed','open','','20-revision-v1','','','2015-04-17 19:14:00','2015-04-17 19:14:00','',20,'/20-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(116,1,'2015-04-17 19:29:43','2015-04-17 19:29:43','I am a 65 year old woman, who was in great pain for almost 10 months. It took 30-45 minutes, 2 canes, and tears to get out of bed every morning. Because of unpredictable spasms, I gave up driving or leaving the house alone. Dr. Maioriello took me as a patient after 4 others refused. He was able to locate the problem and chart a course of treatment. He performed a minimally invasive L3-S1 fusion, and I woke up from the operation in less pain. I walked out of the hospital and have been able to continue with my life.He operated using a minimally invasive technique. He took the time needed to do it correctly. When I awoke after the surgery, I knew things were better. I immediately was able to move without pain. I would recommend anyone who has severe back pain to see Dr. Maioriello. He is very skilled and honest and gives you the information needed to make the decision, if surgery is your answer.','Dorothy H.','','inherit','closed','open','','57-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 19:29:43','2015-04-17 19:29:43','',57,'/57-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(117,1,'2015-04-17 19:34:14','2015-04-17 19:34:14','Dr. Maioriello was born and raised in the suburbs of Chicago. He completed his undergraduate studies in 1993 and earned a bachelors degree in biochemistry from Illinois Benedictine College. After college, he completed a two-year graduate program in less than a year and received his masters degree in neurobiology and physiology from Northwestern University. Dr. Maioriello graduated from Rush Medical College in 1998, and his six year neurosurgical residency was completed at The University of Texas Medical Branch in June of 2004. He practiced minimally invasive spine surgery and general neurosurgery for six years in Davenport, Iowa. However, he wanted to be able to offer comprehensive cerebrovascular services and had the forethought to predict the paradigm shift in the field from open to endovascular surgery. In 2010, Dr. Maioriello closed his solo private practice and moved to Houston for his two-year endovascular neurosurgery fellowship at the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston. In 2012, he completed the fellowship and started Minimally Invasive Brain and Spine; a new comprehensive neurosurgery practice covering Houston and the surrounding suburbs.\r\n\r\nHis comprehensive clinical interests include: endovascular surgery for cerebrovascular disease, intra-arterial management of acute stroke, minimally invasive spine surgery, brain and spine tumor surgery, brain and spine trauma surgery, peripheral nerve surgery, general neurosurgery, neurosurgical intensive care, stereotactic neurosurgery, and the surgical management of neck and low back pain.\r\n\r\n<a class=\"linkedin\" href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/pub/anthony-maioriello/25/a33/436\" target=\"_blank\">View my LinkedIn profile</a>','Anthony V. Maioriello M.D., M.S., FAANS, FACS','','inherit','closed','open','','20-revision-v1','','','2015-04-17 19:34:14','2015-04-17 19:34:14','',20,'/20-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(118,1,'2015-04-17 20:13:16','2015-04-17 20:13:16','','Leatha','','inherit','closed','open','','leatha','','','2015-04-17 20:13:16','2015-04-17 20:13:16','',70,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Leatha.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(119,1,'2015-04-17 20:30:58','2015-04-17 20:30:58','<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Leatha3.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-122\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Leatha3.jpg\" alt=\"Leatha\" width=\"935\" height=\"478\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWithin a month of our arrival in Houston, Texas in 2009, my wife had surgery on her back. From that time on, she seemed to physically deteriorate, until, during the summer of 2011, she began to fall often, for no reason. I t appeared that she lost strength in her right leg, and she was not able to trust herself to move from place to place without having an incident when she would suddenly, for no reason we could ascertain, fall.\r\n\r\nWe saw a number of doctors and surgeons—none of them could figure out what to do. Some of them postulated that would need surgery, but none were willing to do the job. All of the doctors we saw simply gave my wife pain medication; this was, in their words, “To help her manage her pain.” She took a tremendous amount of pain medication, which did not handle the problem. She continued to have problems with her leg, and continued to fall when she moved about the apartment. Her condition deteriorated to the point where, after a hospital stay where she was treated for a subdural hematoma as a result of a fall, she was sent to a rehabilitation center for treatment. But the treatment did not work well—it did not address her condition.\r\n\r\nIn the fall of 2012, while my wife was in the hospital, being seen after another incident where she fell, she met Dr, Maioriello. Dr. Maioriello diagnosed my wife’s condition, realized wht needed to be done, and performed the spinal surgery on my wife.\r\n\r\nThe result—in less than 3 months, she is walking well, and getting stronger every day. The level of pain medication she is taking has reduced dramatically. I believe Dr. Maioriello saved the life of my wife; she would never have gotten better without the surgery he performed on her.\r\n\r\nI cannot stress enough the confidence we have in Dr. Maioriello. In my opinion, we put the life of my wife in his hands - and we won.','Ken and Leatha W.','','inherit','closed','open','','70-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 20:30:58','2015-04-17 20:30:58','',70,'/70-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(120,1,'2015-04-17 20:26:14','2015-04-17 20:26:14','','Leatha','','inherit','closed','open','','leatha-2','','','2015-04-17 20:26:14','2015-04-17 20:26:14','',70,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Leatha1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(121,1,'2015-04-17 20:28:43','2015-04-17 20:28:43','','Leatha','','inherit','closed','open','','leatha-3','','','2015-04-17 20:28:43','2015-04-17 20:28:43','',70,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Leatha2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(122,1,'2015-04-17 20:30:54','2015-04-17 20:30:54','','Leatha','','inherit','closed','open','','leatha-4','','','2015-04-17 20:30:54','2015-04-17 20:30:54','',70,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Leatha3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(123,1,'2015-04-17 20:32:48','2015-04-17 20:32:48','','Joe Aldridge pic','','inherit','closed','open','','joe-aldridge-pic','','','2015-04-17 20:32:48','2015-04-17 20:32:48','',68,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Joe-Aldridge-pic.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(124,1,'2015-04-17 22:53:29','2015-04-17 22:53:29','<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Joe-Aldridge-pic.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-123\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Joe-Aldridge-pic.jpg\" alt=\"Joe Aldridge pic\" width=\"935\" height=\"503\" /></a>\n\nIn November of 2003, the day before Thanksgiving, my then 7-year-old son Joe, was accidentally hit in the head with a golf club. He was lifeflighted to UTMB Galveston where Dr. Maioriello was a resident at the time. On the way to the hospital (we couldn’t ride in the helicopter so we had to make the 1 ½ hour trip by car) we were called and told he needed surgery immediately. He wouldn’t make it until we got there. He had a subdural hematoma and pieces of his skill were embedded in his brain. He lost his speech and was paralyzed on his right side. We were told “if” he made it through surgery, it as doubtful he would ever be the same. My husband and I were devasted. Our outgoing, athletic, happy little boy, who just got his 3rd pee-wee football trophy the weekend before, would possibly never talk or walk again. After several hours of surgery, Dr. Maioriello gave us the best gift anyone could at the time, hope.\n\nIt’s been a very long journey, but my now 11-year-old is an honor student in 6th grade. He is a member of the student council, sports club, and (in his mind a basketball superstar. And best of all, I never thought I would be so thankful for someone who NEVER shuts up!!!\n\nMy Son, my family, and I could never express all the thanks we have for Dr. Maioriello and the entire team of people who turned a horrible tragedy into a miracle. I wish him and his family all the blessings he so greatly deserves.\n<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Joe-aldridge-1st-card.jpg\"><img style=\"display:inline-block;\" class=\"alignleft wp-image-125 size-medium\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Joe-aldridge-1st-card-213x300.jpg\" alt=\"Joe aldridge 1st card\" width=\"213\" height=\"300\" /></a>\n\n<img style=\"display:inline-block;\" class=\"wp-image-126 size-medium centerImage\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/joe_A-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"joe_A\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" /></a> <span style=\"font-size: 0.8em;\">Dr. Maioriello at Joe A.\'s Graduation</span>[/caption]\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I cannot describe the gratefulness I feel in my heart. In this life you met few people that truly stand out and you are one of them. Thank you Dr. Maioriello for saving our son.</p>','Joe A.','In November of 2003, the day before Thanksgiving, my then 7-year-old son Joe, was accidentally hit in the head with a golf club. He was lifeflighted to UTMB Galveston where Dr. Maioriello was a resident at the time. On the way to the hospital (we couldn’t ride in the helicopter so we had to make the 1 ½ hour trip by car) we were called and told he needed surgery immediately. He wouldn’t make it until we got there. He had a subdural hematoma and pieces of his skill were embedded in his brain. He lost his speech and was paralyzed on his right side. We were told “if” he made it through surgery, it as doubtful he would ever be the same. My husband and I were devasted. Our outgoing, athletic, happy little boy, who just got his 3rd pee-wee football trophy the weekend before, would possibly never talk or walk again. After several hours of surgery, Dr. Maioriello gave us the best gift anyone could at the time, hope.','inherit','closed','open','','68-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 22:53:29','2015-04-17 22:53:29','',68,'/68-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(125,1,'2015-04-17 20:33:22','2015-04-17 20:33:22','','Joe aldridge 1st card','','inherit','closed','open','','joe-aldridge-1st-card','','','2015-04-17 20:33:22','2015-04-17 20:33:22','',68,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Joe-aldridge-1st-card.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(126,1,'2015-04-17 20:35:09','2015-04-17 20:35:09','','joe_A','','inherit','closed','open','','joe_a','','','2015-04-17 20:35:09','2015-04-17 20:35:09','',68,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/joe_A.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(127,1,'2015-04-17 20:46:44','2015-04-17 20:46:44','I was referred to Dr. Maioriello by my family doctor. I had been in pain for over two months. I had severe pain in my left hip with pain running down my leg. Each morning, after taking two steps, my leg would go numb from my foot to right below my knee. The MRI revealed a bulging disc in my lower back that was sitting on top of my nerve. Dr. Maioriello performed a minimally invasive L4/LS laminectomy. The very day of the surgery I was home by 3:00. When I awoke three hours later I heard my daughter and granddaughter downstairs. I walked downstairs without ANY discomfort whatsoever. It was truly unbelievable! The very next morning I was in Target, pushing a shopping cart, keeping up with my four year old granddaughter, and buying what I needed for Easter. Since the day of my surgery I have not had one pain in my leg or hip. To me ... Dr. Maioriello performed a miracle! I called my family doctor and thanked him profusely for referring me to Dr. Maioriello.','Janie W.','','inherit','closed','open','','67-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 20:46:44','2015-04-17 20:46:44','',67,'/67-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(128,1,'2015-04-17 20:51:37','2015-04-17 20:51:37','','GeneH','','inherit','closed','open','','geneh','','','2015-04-17 20:51:37','2015-04-17 20:51:37','',65,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/GeneH.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(129,1,'2015-04-17 20:51:46','2015-04-17 20:51:46','<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/GeneH.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-128\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/GeneH.jpg\" alt=\"GeneH\" width=\"768\" height=\"395\" /></a>\r\n\r\nDr. Anthony V. Maioriello went above and beyond as my neurosurgeon. He removed a tumor deep within my brain endoscopically with 100% success. He and his office staff treated me and my family with compassion and understanding during this difficult time. Dr. Maioriello is as real as they come and his expertise and bedside manner are phenomenal. He saved my life, and I would highly recommend him to everyone I know. (Tumor removed 2/21/13)','Gene H.','','inherit','closed','open','','65-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 20:51:46','2015-04-17 20:51:46','',65,'/65-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(130,1,'2015-04-17 20:53:07','2015-04-17 20:53:07','','DerrickF','','inherit','closed','open','','derrickf','','','2015-04-17 20:53:07','2015-04-17 20:53:07','',64,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/DerrickF.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(132,1,'2015-04-17 20:53:58','2015-04-17 20:53:58','Dear Mrs. McDreamy (Bella),\r\nI wish I could eloquently vocalize how thankful I am to you and your family for sharing your husband and his talents with me. I know you and your family make sacrifices everyday because of his profession. It must be difficult at times, but I am grateful to you because I know I could not do what he does without the love and support from his wife and family. Thank you for all you do!\r\n\r\nDear Dr. McDreamy\r\nWords will never adequately express how thankful I am for you. You will always find me singing thanks for all you have done. You enabled me to be present at my daughter’s wedding. This is a once in a lifetime event and I am forever grateful. I pray the Lord give you continued success and happiness in all you do.','Yolanda G.','','inherit','closed','open','','63-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 20:53:58','2015-04-17 20:53:58','',63,'/63-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(133,1,'2015-04-17 20:56:35','2015-04-17 20:56:35','Please accept this letter as a sincere recommendation as to the diagnostic and neurosurgical skills of Dr. Anthony Maioriello. I am a 65-year-old man who has suffered the debilitating effects of a bad back since the age of 29, when my first surgical laminectomy was performed. In 1999 I underwent three discectomies by two different neurosurgeons at Genesis West, both cervical and lumbar. In 2005, I underwent a cervical discectomy by another Davenport neurosurgeon who told me that he doubted the success of his own procedure and that I would have to go to \"Cleveland or St. Louis\'\', where they specialize in \"difficult cases\".\n\nBy referral from my family physician I visited with Dr. Maiorello and underwent a total of three procedures that were \"major\", insofar as they required the insertion of a titanium plate in my cervical region and titanium rods in my lumbar region. All this work was done by Dr. Maiorello in Davenport at a skill level equal to or better than any \"Big City\" or \" Big University \" location.\n\nI am now 99% recovered from my spinal problems and I credit Dr. Maiorello for my major improvement.','Walter R. Z.','','inherit','closed','open','','60-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 20:56:35','2015-04-17 20:56:35','',60,'/60-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(134,1,'2015-04-17 21:04:19','2015-04-17 21:04:19','Over the past 4-6 years I have been to physical therapy several times. I have tried massage therapy. I have had chiropractic treatments. I have done water physical therapy and in just the last 8 months my lower back pain had increased more than I could handle. The pain was affecting my everyday life activities. I couldn\'t do things at work I was normally expected to do. It hurt to cough or sneeze tremendously. I couldn\'t vacuum my own home without being in pain and barely moving around the next day. I was just getting so frustrated at the simple fact that my children and husband had to help me get pants, socks, and shoes on. I just could not accomplish these simple tasks on my own anymore. I was, at the most, getting 2 to 4 hours of sleep and waking up with this unbearable pain down my leg and what I can only imagine a knife stabbing you in the back. I was then sent to have an MRI. This is when my family doctor referred me to the pain clinic. There I went through a series of 3 shots, into the lower back area L-5/S-1. This helped the pain down my leg a little but it was not going away and my back was still in a lot of pain. By then I was using a walker to get out of bed. Getting on and off the toilet became a chore, just because of bending. I then was referred to Dr. Anthony V. Maioriello by two other Neurosurgeons.\n\nDr. Maioriello explained to me that I had Spondylolisthesis. This is a condition where a part of your spine is slipping. Dr. Maioriello was very patient in listening to what I told him had been happening in just the last few months. Dr. Maioriello ordered some x-rays of my back. He then told me I would be a candidate for what is called a Minimally Invasive Transforaminal Lumbar Interbody Fusion L5 to S1 Right. Dr. Maioriello explained , in detail, all the risks involved in a major surgery like this. He went over the surgery procedure in detail. My husband and I still knew, with all the risks involved, I had to have this done.\n\nThe surgery was scheduled for Thursday March 22nd. On Friday the 23rd Dr. Maioriello came to the hospital and asked how I was feeling. I told him I had not felt this good for at least 8 months. I was up walking 3 hours after surgery and every chance the nurses had time, I was asking to go for a walk. I was walking with no help by Friday afternoon and sitting down and getting back up from the toilet with no problem. I could even stretch like normal (arms above your head) and my back did not hurt. I could not do this before surgery. Dr. Anthony Maioriello was happy with my progress.\n\nThe second week after surgery I rode with a friend to the mall and walked around (with a few rests of course) for about 6 hours. It has been 3 weeks since my surgery and I haven\'t walked this normal in at least 8 months. I had a little pain down one leg but it is getting to the point where I think it will be gone completely in another week. I am looking forward to physical therapy now. I just know my life is already on the road to a normal everyday living. I am sleeping all night and that means ALOT! I am looking forward to the walks in the parks with my husband and children.\n\nI would recommend Doctor Anthony V. Maioriello from Midwest Brain and Spine 3400 Dexter Ct. Suite 200 in Davenport IA 52807 to anyone in the world for this operation if needed. I know I have months of healing and physical therapy but I\'d just like to say, \"THANK YOU SO MUCH, Dr. Maioriello for making my life better already!','Patty M.','','inherit','closed','open','','59-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 21:04:19','2015-04-17 21:04:19','',59,'/59-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(136,1,'2015-04-17 21:07:18','2015-04-17 21:07:18','','LEAD Technologies Inc. V1.01','','inherit','closed','open','','lead-technologies-inc-v1-01','','','2015-04-17 21:07:18','2015-04-17 21:07:18','',58,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Scottie.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(137,1,'2015-04-17 21:11:42','2015-04-17 21:11:42','','pam','','inherit','closed','open','','pam','','','2015-04-17 21:11:42','2015-04-17 21:11:42','',56,'/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/pam.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(138,1,'2015-04-17 21:12:13','2015-04-17 21:12:13','<a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/pam.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-137\" src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/pam.jpg\" alt=\"pam\" width=\"835\" height=\"380\" /></a>\n\nOn June 4, 2007, our lives changed forever. That day, our Mom, grandma, great-grandma, sister, aunt, wife, and friend to all, Pam A., suffered a major stroke. By no coincidence, God sent Dr. Maioriello to help.\n\nDuring our family’s initial consultation regarding Mom’s condition with “Dr. Tony” (as he became known to us), our family immediately felt comfortable with him and knew he was the one with the skill and compassion to return Mom to us. He calmly explained to a shocked family what had happened and how he was going to try and fix the problem. Five hours later after surgery, Dr. Tony again explained the situation and prognosis. He gave it to us straight which we appreciated. The next day, when the CT scan showed additional bleeding on the brain, he explained the challenging situation she was facing. Because of our confidence in him and our unwavering belief that God had a different plan other than death at this time for Mom, our family gave him the go-ahead to return to surgery. This time, Dr. Tony spent nearly nine hours in a second emergency surgery with Mom after having spent the earlier part of his day with another surgery. Although we agonized during the surgeries for the outcome, we always knew Mom was in very caring and skilled hands. Upon completion of the second surgery, he immediately updated us on the seriousness of Mom’s condition. There was still tremendous bleeding on Mom’s brain, and they needed a special clotting agent transported from Iowa City to help. For the next five days, our family prayed for Mom to awaken and to recover from the stroke. Dr. Tony never gave up on Mom!\n\nIt is nearly six months since Mom’s stroke and she is a miracle! Mom continues to improve each day. She has completed physical therapy and walks without assistance. She will wrap-up her occupational and speech therapies in a few weeks. Mom continues to be our family’s glue. There are few people who have been through so much and have shown such grace, strength and determination as she. Several weeks after Mom left the hospital, she shared a story about first meeting Dr. Tony. Days after surgery and still heavily sedated, Dr. Maioriello stopped by for one of his many visits. Mom thought he said his name was “Dr. Marshmallow.” She still chuckles about it!\n\nThe Ahrens family is deeply grateful for how Dr. Tony treated Mom, and also our family. We are reminded of his skill every time Mom utters a joke or helps with dishwashing. He made certain we were informed and involved at all points along the way. We also take comfort in knowing Dr. Tony, a humble man, recognizes a higher power at work as well. During Mom’s check-up appointment with Dr. Tony weeks after the surgeries, we were speechless when Mrs. Maioriello presented Mom with a homemade chocolate cake to celebrate – what a class act! What a gift God provides us when he introduces us to special angels here on earth. Dr. Tony certainly will always be our special angel!','Pam A.','','inherit','closed','open','','56-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 21:12:13','2015-04-17 21:12:13','',56,'/56-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(139,1,'2015-04-17 21:15:53','2015-04-17 21:15:53','Dr. Maioriello, to all who read.\n\nMy many thanks to Dr. Maioriello for his outstanding skill, compassionate manner and professionalism.\n\nI came to Dr. Maioriello as a young very active 51-year-old male that (had) multiple issues, the most prominent (I thought) my lower-back discomfort.\n\nDuring my initial consultation, Dr. Maioriello picked-up on my hyper-reflexivity, noting that it is a sign of concern. A spinal MRI revealed two herniated disks in my neck, what a surprise, if an accident occurred I could be paralyzed!\n\nDr. Maioriello is genuinely concerned that his patients have the information to make proper decisions, their wellness and peace of mind.\n\nWhen I made the decision to move forward with the procedure I felt part of a team, even just prior to surgery. In need of mention is Dr. Maioriello’s wife Bella who manages the business and the staff, good folks.\n\nWhen you select a surgeon you hope that the person has what it takes, let me tell you, my second walk just hours after surgery, I was halfway around the building and realized I had no back pain, I cried, literally, I was so happy. I can only tell you.','Greg L.','','inherit','closed','open','','15-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-17 21:15:53','2015-04-17 21:15:53','',15,'/15-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(141,1,'2015-06-04 20:29:57','2015-06-04 20:29:57','','FinancialPolicy_6-2015','','inherit','closed','open','','financialpolicy_6-2015','','','2015-06-04 20:29:57','2015-06-04 20:29:57','',85,'http://www.minimallyinvasivebrainandspine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/FinancialPolicy_6-2015.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(142,1,'2015-06-04 20:30:17','2015-06-04 20:30:17','<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/MIBS_New_Patient_Packet_No2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">New Patient Packet</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Financial  Policy 2015\" href=\"http://www.minimallyinvasivebrainandspine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/FinancialPolicy_6-2015.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Financial Policy 2015</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Auth_to_Release_to_Family.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Authorization to Release to Family</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Hippa_2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Privacy Practices / HIPPA</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--li><a href=\"#\" target=\"_blank\">Authorization to Release Healthcare Information</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"#\" target=\"_blank\">Patient Authorization for Disclosure of Protected Health Information</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"#\" target=\"_blank\">Life Insurance Plans</a></li-->','Patient Forms and Information','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-v1','','','2015-06-04 20:30:17','2015-06-04 20:30:17','',85,'http://www.minimallyinvasivebrainandspine.com/85-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
